Style rules: match the repo's conventional-commit style. Use `chore` only for repo maintenance. Omit the scope when the change spans multiple subsystems. Most commits need a body. Include a body when the change is non-trivial: multi-file changes, behavior changes, refactors affecting APIs or data structures, migration notes, or when the *why* is not obvious from the diff. One-liner subjects (no body) are only for trivial changes like typo fixes or single-file cosmetic changes. For complex changes use the detailed trio: `## Body Summary` (what and why), `## Body Details` (edge cases, design decisions, alternatives), `## Body Footer` (migration, breaking changes, Fixes #123). Avoid vague subjects: Bad "chore: update files" -> Good "feat(mcp): add structured commit retries" with body. Bad "fix: stuff" -> Good "fix(parser): preserve prefixed transcript lines" with body.

Document shape: a markdown document whose frontmatter carries the decision. For a commit, use `type: commit` plus `subject:` in the frontmatter, then either one `## Body` section OR the detailed trio (one `- [ID] text` item per section, never both), plus optional `## Files` (one item per file) and `## Excluded Files` (items formatted `path | reason`; valid reasons: internal_ignore, not_task_related, sensitive, deferred). When no commit is needed, submit only frontmatter `type: skip` with `reason: <why>`.

